caption:

And Dear New York passed them all in foot traffic, in less than two weeks!

caption: A few years ago I received a DM from @zohrankmamdani. Only recently did I discover its existence. It was a very unusual DM‚Äîespecially coming from a local assemblyman who would soon be running for higher office. He had very little name recognition at the time, and could have benefited from publicity. But unlike the thousands of messages I‚Äôve received from people with something to promote, Zohran did not ask to be featured on Humans of New York. Instead he asked if he could introduce me to taxi drivers that were struggling beneath the burden of debt. Coming from a man with political ambitions, this self-denying request was so strange as to be almost singular. I don‚Äôt endorse politicians on Humans of New York. But I‚Äôll endorse a good man. And it was a good man who cleared 30 minutes from his schedule yesterday to swing by Grand Central to visit Dear New York. Nearly fifty student artists were visiting that day with their families, and I thought a surprise visit from this widely-loved future mayor would be a special memory for all of them. Before Zohran‚Äôs arrival I was convinced I‚Äôd made a terrible mistake. The Vanderbilt Hall exhibit was filled to capacity with adult visitors. Dear New York is self-funded so there was very little staff and security for crowd control. In the crush of people I was almost certain this special day for the kids would devolve into thirty minutes of selfie requests. But everyone rose to the occasion. Hundreds of adults quickly cleared the room and stood outside the exhibit. Eleven very notable adult artists are also featured in the exhibition, but even they took a step back, so that these students could briefly have the stage to themselves. Each child stood by their work and Zohran was able to meet all of them, one at a time, and honor their contributions to the most-visited art show in New York City. Thanks to everyone who ceded the stage yesterday to make this moment possible. Thank you Zohran for literally sitting down on the floor so that these young artists could feel so tall. Thank you for continually centering other people in your life and work. And thank you, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

caption: Dear New York closes in four short days. It has been an absolutely magical and historic two weeks. But it is not yet a finished work. Dear New York is an immersive art installation by people, for people, and about people. Everyone who visits Grand Central Station becomes part of it. With the crowds seeming to grow 20% each passing day, the work continues to grow more and more meaningful. Come join us this weekend as Dear New York reaches full bloom. When you arrive you will find a Grand Central completely cleared of advertising. If you come by subway, you‚Äôll enter through an immersive installation covering all three levels of Grand Central subway station, designed by @trabuccocampos and his team at @pentagramdesign. You‚Äôll then emerge into an iconic main concourse which has been completely transformed with light projections into a showcase of NYC‚Äôs humanity. For the first time in history, the main concourse has also been transformed by two weeks of musical programming performed by the celebrated students and alumni of @juilliardschool . After taking in a performance, be sure to swing by Vanderbilt Hall to experience the most-visited, most-talked-about art exhibit in town, designed by the legendary @davidkorins , and featuring the work of eleven highly notable NYC photographers alongside the work of 600 school-aged student artists‚Äîevery participant given the same museum-quality printing and framing by @pictonewyork .  At 8 PM on Sunday night, there will be a short closing ceremony featuring a performance by a 200-strong chorus from @ypcofnyc. Afterwards Dear New York will go dark forever. It is incredibly tragic that it must die so soon. But also, that‚Äôs the reason it‚Äôs so alive.

caption: We‚Äôve lost a legend. Stephanie ‚ÄòTanqueray‚Äô Johnson passed away last night after suffering a severe stroke. She will be most remembered for holding the world in thrall with her no-holds-barred storytelling about life as a burlesque dancer in the 1970‚Äôs. Stephanie was a complicated person. Her public persona was irresistibly charismatic. Yet behind the scenes I‚Äôve rarely met somebody who had such difficulty with close relationships. She was internationally adored, yet intensely lonely. She was desirous of companionship, yet quick to cut people out of her life over the smallest slights. Stephanie told me endless stories about how badly her mother treated her as a child, yet remained capable of exhibiting that same behavior toward others. People are complicated. And the longer you live, the more you realize the most inexcusable behavior often stems from the saddest traumas. There was always a little girl inside of Stephanie who never had a chance to feel safe. A little girl who learned at a young age that the best way to keep from getting hurt was to throw the first punch. But this little girl also had such a love of life. And despite her X-rated stories, and her sharp edges, was capable of such innocence. Stephanie slept with a teddy bear until the day she died. She‚Äôd melt in the presence of animals and babies. And until the very end, she laughed like a little girl. In the final weeks of her life all the hard edges melted away. All the defense mechanisms, the learned responses. She reverted back to the little girl she‚Äôd been before she‚Äôd gotten hurt. And that is the Stephanie that is smiling down on us right now. In her own words: ‚ÄòWhen I get to heaven I hope God shows me a movie of my life. But just the funny parts. Not the in-between parts, cause then we‚Äôd both start crying. Underneath all the laughs and the gags, it was always about one thing: survival. Tanqueray was a lot of fun. But Tanqueray was Stephanie. And Stephanie was a teenage runaway from Albany: doing what she needed to do, and being who she needed to be, to get what she needed to get.‚Äù I love ya, Steph. Thanks for taking me, and all of us, on the greatest ride of our lives.

caption: ‚ÄúI‚Äôve decided to go back to school today; I was just accepted into college, and I made the decision to enroll. I happened to be wearing my Coney Island shirt, so I decided to come out here and sit by the water. I used to come out here all the time. For many years I was in an extremely difficult marriage. I‚Äôd never say anything hurtful about my ex-wife, because there‚Äôs still a lot of love there‚Äî but there were times when I had to get away. And this is where I‚Äôd go. I ended up leaving the marriage right before the pandemic. I had to completely start over. I went from having my own apartment, and having all the things you‚Äôre supposed to have, to sleeping on a mattress on the floor. I never stopped teaching my voice and music lessons. I was still expanding, still growing. But I went through a lot of hardship. There was so much responsibility on me. My mother is 94; she has dementia. I was taking care of her too. For the longest time I‚Äôve never had any room for something going on in my own life. So this is a very big thing for me‚Äîgoing back to school. I‚Äôm going to major in social work because I‚Äôd like to introduce a therapy element to my voice lessons. If I‚Äôm being honest, part of the reason is I need more clients. I‚Äôm not somebody who has a big retirement saved. I‚Äôm turning 65 soon and I‚Äôm no longer very competitive in an ageist music world. So money is part of it. But also, voice lessons are such a wonderful tool for self-actualization. I‚Äôve noticed when people are learning to sing, they come up against so many things that are holding them back. They‚Äôll meet with embarrassment. They‚Äôll meet their inner critic. They‚Äôll have moments where they think: that‚Äôs too loud, that‚Äôs too shrill. But they have to push past it. Because In order to fill the room, you first need a sense of being worthy enough to express yourself. You can‚Äôt say: I‚Äôm going to sing like this person. No, you‚Äôre going to sound like you. There are tools you can learn to sound like the best version of you, but you will sound like you. And it‚Äôs such a privilege to be present when people discover that for the first time: you can sing just like yourself, and it can be beautiful.‚Äù

caption: Last night someone asked me what part of Dear New York I‚Äôm proudest of; this was hard to answer. But I can tell you what‚Äôs filled my heart the most. Many in the press are calling it ‚ÄòThe Children‚Äôs Exhibit,‚Äô because Dear New York‚Äôs Vanderbilt Hall features the work of six hundred NYC student artists. Each student was asked to photograph and write about someone who has made a difference in their lives. Some of these artists are as young as four, and their photography might not be the most technically polished, but there is a striking intimacy that can only come from photographing someone you love. The written profiles which accompany the photographs are extremely touching, and collectively represent the millions of invisible, unsung heroes that form the bedrock of NYC‚Äôs community. It‚Äôs not the mayors and the movie stars that form the heart of this city. It‚Äôs the mothers, the fathers, the teachers, the social workers, and the millions of other people who show up every day in the lives of others. One reason the ‚ÄòChildren‚Äôs Exhibit‚Äô lands so deeply is that its amplified by a sister exhibition featuring eleven highly notable NYC photographers. Among them are living legends such as @jamelshabazz , a trailblazer in street portraiture. As well as Gugenheim Fellow @sarabennettbrooklyn , a former public defender who profiles formerly-incarcerated women. The two exhibits are blended seamlessly in an innovative, immersive design by @davidkorins . The most beautiful part of these blended exhibits is that all 611 artists‚Äî young and old, beginning and established‚Äî have been given the same museum-quality framing and presentation. The result is an egalitarian, non-hierarchical ode to the diversity, humanity, and community of this city.  The exhibit has been overflowing all week, from open to close, and I‚Äôm not sure I‚Äôve ever seen an art installation elicit so much emotion. Dear New York closes on Sunday. caption: How does a two-week art installation about community grow into something like this? I think it‚Äôs because people are tired of ‚Äòconnecting‚Äô through screens. Nobody wants to live in a metaverse, whatever the hell that is. We don‚Äôt want to become passive consumers of songs that ‚Äòseem‚Äô human, art that ‚Äòseems‚Äô human, friends that ‚Äòseem‚Äô human. None of this stuff is what we need. We need to create. We need to connect. We need to serve other people if we‚Äôre going to have any sort of place or belonging in this world. If humanity is going to thrive‚Äî and if art is going to thrive ‚Äì there is only one place for it to go: the real world. Dear New York was founded upon the increasingly rare belief that humanity is pretty freaking amazing. This isn‚Äôt a perfect world. Every day the media brings us new examples of glaring injustice and senseless violence. We still have much work to do. But while we do the work, let us not forget how much love there is in this world. In New York City alone, in a single day, there are millions of stories of people taking care of each other. These stories don‚Äôt make the evening news, but they‚Äôre no less real. And when you sum it all up‚Äîthe good and the bad ‚Äì humanity is still worth fighting for. It‚Äôs still something to celebrate. Dear New York will close tomorrow at 8 pm, with a short choral performance by hundreds of children from @ypcofnyc .

caption: Dear New York might be the largest public art installation in decades. All of Grand Central Station has been transformed into a celebration of the diversity and humanity of New York City. As part of Dear New York, there is a Steinway Concert Grand Piano in the center of the main concourse. During the day the piano is played by some of the world‚Äôs most talented pianists, selected by @juilliardschool . But after 10 pm something magical happens. The piano is made available (through a submission process) to all sorts of New Yorkers. The only requirement: a fierce passion for playing piano. There were well over a thousand submissions and only a small amount could be selected. But among these are some beautiful, beautiful stories. Dear New York closes this Sunday. It has been such a magical run.

caption: I‚Äôd like to conclude with one final story that I think captures the spirit of Dear New York. During the final hour before Sunday‚Äôs closing ceremony there was no performer scheduled on the Steinway Concert Grand, so I loudly invited everyone in the crowd to take a turn. About six or seven random New Yorkers stepped forward, bravely volunteering for this once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to play the world‚Äôs finest piano for a huge crowd of people in Grand Central Station. It was such a joyous and communal experience. Each person played one song. Everyone was at-least-a-little nervous, but everyone nailed it under the brightest possible spotlight. Eventually one of the producers whispered that it was time to wrap up, but before I could tell everyone ‚ÄòGoodnight,‚Äô I noticed the tiniest little hand being raised. It belonged to a six-year-old girl wearing a denim jacket, sparkly cowboy boots, and a small plastic princess crown. I knelt down and asked her name; she told me ‚ÄòCharlotte.‚Äô I asked Charlotte if she wanted a chance to play, and she nodded with conviction. Her mother‚Äî half-proud, half-terrified‚Äîquickly told me that Charlotte had a keyboard at home, but had never played piano before. This small distinction did not bother Charlotte one bit. With the confidence of Liberace, she marched up to the Steinway, took a seat, and played piano for the very first time, in front of hundreds of people. I‚Äôm not sure anyone beyond the first row could hear it. But I am sure that everyone could feel it. Immediately following her performance, two hundred young singers from The Young People‚Äôs Chorus of New York City brought Dear New York to a close with an epic performance. (Video clip in carousel.) Thank you Charlotte, thank you @ypcofnyc, and thank you everyone, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

caption: The first copies of Dear New York have arrived. This one is deeply personal; holding it in my hand is like holding three years of my life. it opens with a longform HONY story‚Äî think Tanqueray, think Detra, think Venus‚Äî except this time it‚Äôs the story of my own attempt to capture the people of this city. The book then expands into four hundred full-color portraits and stories. Unlike previous Humans of New York books: 75 percent of these stories have not been shared online. Dear New York was lovingly created to be the most special thing that‚Äôs ever come out of Humans of New York. It will make you think, it will make you laugh, it will make you cry. It‚Äôs my love letter to this city, and I can‚Äôt wait to share it with you this October. But if you could do me a favor: if you think you‚Äôll be getting Dear New York this fall, consider locking in your order now. Preorders have never been more crucial to helping launch a book into the world. The book has yet to be heavily discounted, but I know Amazon and Barnes and Noble specifically will retroactively apply the inevitable future discounts to your order. Thanks everyone! Link in bio.

caption: Eleven years ago I received a DM from some guy named Lin-Manuel Miranda. I‚Äôd never heard of him. He had about 30,000 Twitter followers at the time. He‚Äôd created a critically acclaimed show called ‚ÄòIn The Heights,‚Äô but I wasn‚Äôt fluent enough with Broadway for that to ring a bell. In his DM he told me to ‚Äòholler‚Äô at him if I ever came up to Washington Heights. A few weeks later, that‚Äôs exactly what I did. Why? Because I needed a Spanish interpreter, and I wanted to know if he‚Äôd consider accompanying me while I collected stories. Lin informed me that this would not be possible, because he‚Äôd just come home from the hospital with his newborn son. ‚ÄòOh, really?‚Äô I asked. And that‚Äôs how I randomly took the first portrait of the brand-new Miranda family. Lin mentioned at the time that he was working on ‚Äòsome play about Alexander Hamilton.‚Äô Four months later Hamilton would have its off-Broadway premiere at the Public Theater. And well, the rest is history. I‚Äôve always treasured this small intersection I had with Lin before the rocket ship took off. Not because I got to watch him change. But because I got to watch how little he changed. He‚Äôs remained the same good man I met that day: enamored with his newborn son, enamored with his wife, enamored with life. He‚Äôs gone on to compose music for so many celebrated films, modeling that zest for life to millions of children around the world‚Äî including my own. (I‚Äôm a Moana man myself, with all due respect to the Family Madrigal.) But what I‚Äôve most admired about Lin is how much he supports other people. I‚Äôm not sure I‚Äôve ever seen someone use their platform to so consistently highlight and uplift fellow artists. In that vein, he immediately agreed when I asked if he‚Äôd drop by Dear New York to play the Steinway Concert Grand. He spent days trying to lower my expectations. ‚ÄòI‚Äôm not a pianist,‚Äô he said. ‚ÄòAll I can do is noodle on the keys.‚Äô And that‚Äôs exactly what he did this morning. He ‚Äònoodled‚Äô his way into the memories and lives of hundreds of very surprised people in Grand Central Station. Thank you @lin_manuel , for always reaching behind you to lift others up. And thank you for being such an important part of Dear New York.

caption: At 9:53 PM last night in Grand Central Station, an absolute shockwave was sent through the music world. At Dear New York Grand Central, six-year-old Whitney Guo Szakacs delivered what music critics could only breathlessly describe as ‚Äòundoubtedly the greatest performance ever staged in a public transit hub by a six-year-old staying up past her bedtime.‚Äô Following Whitney‚Äôs recent world debut for a crowd of twenty residents at the New Jewish Nursing Home, it seemed that her star could not climb any higher. Until she sat down at that Steinway Concert Grand in the center of the world and stunned onlookers with the one song she knows. A mighty song. A song played with such grace and beauty that it might as well have been a million songs. Whitney‚Äôs preparations for this big moment could only be described as Olympian. She took an hour-and-a-half nap, ate some Pad Thai, and said ‚ÄòI believe in myself‚Äô nearly thirty times. When asked about her epoch-defining performance, Whitney remarked: ‚ÄòIn the beginning it was scary. But it wasn‚Äôt scary at the end, because it was all done.‚Äô Thank you, Whitney, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

alt: Photo by Humans of New York on October 11, 2025. May be an image of text.

caption: I'd like to offer a very special opportunity. This is not an opportunity for everyone-- but for someone, it will be a dream come true. As many of you know I am staging a public art installation in Grand Central from October 6th through October 19th, called Dear New York. It is the largest event in the 112-year history of Grand Central, and the entire building has been transformed into a piece of art celebrating the people of this city. 100 percent of advertising has been removed from the building and replaced with portraits and stories from Humans of New York. It was important to me, both spiritually and artistically, to share this iconic stage and canvas with other artists. I knew that Dear New York would never correctly represent New York unless its creators were as diverse as the work itself. In the end over 1000 artists contributed to Dear New York, making it one of the largest pieces of public art in history. Importantly, nobody was asked to work for free: Dear New York involved over $500,000 in direct payments to artists. Which finally brings us to the opportunity: as part of Dear New York, Steinway has donated a Model D Concert Grand, which has been placed in the center of Grand Central's main concourse. This is the most legendary piano in the world, in one of the world's most iconic public spaces. It is the rarest of events and God bless the secretly-artistic-souls at the MTA for allowing this civic gift. @juilliardschool has stepped up to provide musical programming for the entire two weeks of the installation. That is-- until 10 pm each night -- when this most legendary of pianos, in this most legendary of rooms, goes silent. In the spirit of Dear New York, I want to open this stage to other New York pianists. If you are interested in playing for one late-night hour, write to me at dearnysubmissions@gmail.com. Obviously this piano must be treated with great dignity and respect. Please include a link to a video of you playing. (Nothing that needs to be downloaded, please.) But more importantly: tell me what this experience would mean to you. Tell me why you love piano. Selected musicians will be paid $500 for a one hour shift. Please spread the word.

caption: ‚ÄúI‚Äôve been closely guarding a secret. But before I share it, a little context: fifteen years ago I moved to New York to begin Humans of New York. This city has provided me with the most blessed life any one person can ask for. And when I say ‚Äòthis city,‚Äô I mean one thing: it‚Äôs people. For me, New York has always been the people. Many of you know that tomorrow my next book Dear New York will be released. It is my love letter to the city, and I‚Äôve never been prouder of a work I‚Äôve created‚Äîuntil now. Because here is my secret: the book is the inspiration for a much larger piece of art. For the next two weeks Grand Central Station will undergo the biggest transformation in its 112-year history, as it becomes a living, breathing celebration of the people of New York. All advertising has been removed from the building and replaced with portraits and stories from Humans of New York. But it doesn‚Äôt stop there. Grand Central was far too large a canvas for one person, so more than 1000 artists have joined me to contribute to this vision. Some of my collaborators have big reputations, such as @davidkorins, and @juilliardschool, and @pentagramdesign. But none of us are more important than the 600 school children who will exhibit their photography in Vanderbilt Hall. Dear New York is far too large to describe in one post; it will cover all of Grand Central, including all three levels of the subway station. You‚Äôll be hearing much more about my collaborators and their contributions over these next two weeks. But for now I can tell you this: Dear New York was lovingly and carefully made, by some of the greatest people I‚Äôve ever worked with. And if it provides even the slightest amount of joy, solace, beauty, or connection to the 750,000 people who pass through Grand Central every day‚Äîwe have achieved our goal.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúWe started with eight kids from the projects; my son and seven other kids. But that first year we grew to 75 kids. Now we‚Äôve got different teams, different coaches. I pay for a lot of this stuff myself. It‚Äôs sad, because some of the parents‚Ä¶ well, maybe they just don‚Äôt have money. Because I refuse to think that they don‚Äôt care. Because if you don‚Äôt care, and you just leave them in the street‚Äîso much can happen, so easily. And I don‚Äôt want that for them. I want them to do something with their life. They count on me. So if they count on me, if they‚Äôre able to show up, how does it look for me not to show up for them? I have to show up for them. I have to show up for them. Some of these kids have been with me four years. It‚Äôs been a great pleasure to watching them grow: going from not knowing how to catch, to knowing how to catch, to getting baseball ready. But baseball is just the vessel to get them in. As you can see, we don‚Äôt just come play baseball and leave. We barbecue every two weeks. We have a lot of events with the kids: trunk-or-treat, Christmas giveaways, birthday parties. It‚Äôs not just come play ball, I‚Äôll see you next week. It‚Äôs everything. It‚Äôs a family. Let‚Äôs grow this into where you can have friends for the rest of your life. There‚Äôs a lot of troubled kids getting into fights and doing things like that. But if they become your friend, you don‚Äôt want to fight with your friend. You want to protect your friend.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúWe went to dinner and a movie every Tuesday night, until the day she died. Tuesday was our night. My gift back to the woman who gave me everything. My father had a very bad gambling addiction. People were knocking on our doors late at night, looking for money. So my mom took us kids out of the situation and started working two jobs. She‚Äôd take both a train and a bus to get into the city. Then she‚Äôd come back to the Bronx, make us dinner, and head straight to her job as a cashier. When I was sixteen years old, she got a $500 bonus for Christmas. She saw that I was becoming a man, so she bought me my first set of nice clothes. Spent the entire $500 on me. I did what I could to lessen her stress. I walked a very straight line: never drank, never did drugs. All that mattered to me was making sure she retired at a young age. I became a cop, I started paying all her bills. It was important to me that she never tax her body again. But I was a lousy cop. I was so soft that I couldn‚Äôt even write tickets. I ended up packing my bags and moving out to Vegas, hoping to get a restaurant job in one of the casinos. But nobody would hire me. I was getting desperate, down to my last $500. And that‚Äôs when my grandfather died. This man was like a father figure to me. I was heartbroken. I was out of money. And I couldn‚Äôt even tell my mother the truth, because I knew she‚Äôd start working again. It was a Sunday, and I happened to drive past a Catholic church that was being built. They were financing construction by selling plaques for $500. And look‚Äî I don‚Äôt force religion on anybody. Even my kids. But I do tell them: ‚ÄòPlease, believe in something. Because your mother and I won‚Äôt be able to answer all your questions. Life will put you in situations that require something deeper.‚Äô And all those years ago, on that Sunday in Vegas, I just believed with all my heart that Christ was on my side. So I took my last $500 and bought a plaque in honor of my grandfather. The next day I opened the paper and saw a job opening at a bistro. I bullshitted my way into the position, and twelve months later I was running four locations. Catherine Palladino never worked another day in her life.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúTo raise a son, not from her own body, for thirty years‚Äînobody accepts this easily. But my biological mother was under a lot of stress; I was one of triplets. So my aunt volunteered to raise me as her own. She never got married; it was always just the two of us; that‚Äôs why I call her Mom. She was like an angel‚Äî she did everything for me, took care of every need. She used to pray for me all the time: ‚ÄòAllah yarda  øalayk.‚Äô This is difficult to translate, but it means: ‚ÄòMay God be satisfied with you.‚Äô All the time she prayed this. And God was listening. The rest of the family thought she spoiled me too much, and I would never amount to anything. For a while it seemed like they might be right. In university I tried to major in English commerce but I got stuck on it, and failed out of school. It made my Mom look bad. My other siblings were very committed, very religious‚Äî so it seemed like she had bad luck raising a kid. But she never gave up on me. She kept praying: ‚ÄòAllah yarda  øalayk.‚Äô When I changed my field to nursing, she tried to discourage me. She‚Äôd been a nurse her whole life, so she knew how difficult it was. But I told her: I want to be a nurse too, so I‚Äôll always have something to remind me of you. I did my best and got very good grades. When I got a job at the hospital, I treated many of our relatives. They‚Äôd return home and tell my mom: ‚ÄòWow. Yehya took care of us. He got us everything we needed.‚Äô This is what she had always prayed for- for people to say good things about me. It‚Äôs all she ever wanted, and she got to see it. With my salary I helped her buy a new house. It‚Äôs gone now, it got bombed. But we were able to live there for two years together. She got to meet my daughter Zainab, who I named after her. She got to see all these things. She passed away right before the war, thank God. She would not have been able to handle it. And she died exactly how she wanted to die. It was sudden. Maybe a stroke, or an embolism that stuck in her heart. And I was there; I got to hold her in my arms as she passed away. If you‚Äôd have asked how she wanted to die, she would have told you: exactly this way. It‚Äôs what she always prayed for. And God was listening.‚Äù

caption: When I started Humans of New York I had only been photographing for three months. I had no idea what I was doing. But I was bailed out by the explosion of social media, sheer determination, and the power of a good idea. I was a twenty-six-year-old kid with this crazy dream to tell the story of New York City, one person at a time. And it worked. The first Humans of New York book sold almost a million copies‚Äî but even then, I was only beginning to figure out the craft. In the twelve years since I have learned so much: about photography, about interviewing, about writing, about people. And I was moved by the urge to do it again. I wanted to try my best to capture this city; only this time, I knew exactly what I was doing. For nearly two years I took a step back from social media. I focused on one thing: this book. I collected hundreds of stories from all over this city, with the hope that Dear New York would become the most enduring piece of this crazy idea I had, all those years ago. In all the madness and joy of what‚Äôs happening at Grand Central this week, I want to pause for a moment to honor and introduce the book that inspired it all. Dear New York is based on a simple idea: This city is humanity itself. Every type of person is here: every ethnicity, every culture, every belief, every viewpoint. And all of us are crammed onto the same narrow sidewalks, packed into the same subway cars. We sometimes annoy the hell out of each other, but we also show up for each other. We take care of each other. In a world that can seem to be teetering on the edge, New York remains something to celebrate. Humanity remains something to celebrate. Dear New York is published today. It was made with all my heart, and I very much hope that you love it.

caption: I have a confession to make. I have not been 100 percent truthful. All week, in interviews and social media posts, I have been repeating the false claim that Dear New York has transformed ‚Äòall of Grand Central‚Äô into a piece of art celebrating the people and community of this city. I got a little caught up in the hype. This statement was not exactly true, and I apologize. I would now like to correct the record. Dear New York has entirely transformed the historic main concourse. It has transformed every level of the massive Grand Central subway system with an immersive installation designed by @trabuccocampos and his team at @pentagramdesign. It has transformed 150 digital screens, and all available signage into a celebration of the people of this city. It has filled the air with musical programming from @juilliardschool. It has transformed Grand Central‚Äôs stunning Vanderbilt Hall into a ‚Äòcrowd favorite‚Äô exhibit  designed by @davidkorins which blends the work of 600 student artists with established artists, including the living legend @jamelshabazz. But here is where I got a little carried away. If you were one of the tens of thousands of people who became part of Dear New York yesterday, you might have noticed that the Vanderbilt Hall exhibit was closed. Alas, the truth cannot stay buried long: Dear New York was unable to secure 100 percent of Grand Central for the entirety of these two weeks. Exactly one thing was already on the calendar. Last night, Saturday October 11th, the first wedding Grand Central has seen in fifteen years took place in Vanderbilt Hall. But oh, what a beautiful inconvenience. Because how could you possibly celebrate the diversity and humanity of this city‚Ä¶. without a wedding. Congratulations to David and Meredith Garrett. Thank you for taking a small break from your big night, stepping out from behind the curtain, and becoming an important part of Dear New York.

caption: ‚ÄúOne time we were playing in the yard of the school, and the gates were open, and the watchman, he was so precious, he was praying. So we packed our bags and ran for it. There were five of us girls. The watchman saw us and began to call us back, and all of them ran back, except for me. I kept running. The only thing is‚ÄîI literally had nowhere to go. My uncles worked in the middle of the city. If I went there, they would see me. Nothing ever happens in Gaza City without everyone finding out and everyone talking about it. So I just went home. That‚Äôs the thing about this place; it‚Äôs the only place I feel like I belong, but it was always so suffocating. There wasn‚Äôt even space for a teenager to be rebellious. I think the craziest thing we did was paint on walls. Like all teenagers we were convinced that everything was so dark, and the world was ending. So we‚Äôd graffiti Pink Floyd and Cold Play lyrics onto walls: ‚ÄòLights will guide you home.‚Äô Meanwhile home is literally two blocks away, two streets away. The entire neighborhood is rubble now. Honestly I don‚Äôt even like to talk about the past because it feels like the world keeps begging us to prove that we‚Äôre human beings. And if we could only do that, if we could prove that we once lived in nice houses, and listened to Cold Play, then we could prove that we deserve to live and eat and exist and survive. I hate it. I hate pity so much, because it belittles the person you‚Äôre pitying. Please don‚Äôt feel sorry for me. Don‚Äôt feel sorry for us. We don‚Äôt need you, I promise. We don‚Äôt need anyone. We have farmers with farmlands, but they cannot harvest their own farmlands without being shot. We have fishermen who can collect fish from the sea, but they‚Äôre banned from using the sea. We have these beautiful, beautiful cuisines. We can feed ourselves. Just let us, we‚Äôve reached that point. Just let us. Don‚Äôt feel sorry for us. Feel sorry for yourselves, that you‚Äôre living in a country that is arming Israel, that is sending weapons overseas to kill children. Your bombs are killing children. If that bothers you, then don‚Äôt feel sorry for us. Feel sorry for yourself. That you don‚Äôt have enough say in your own country to stop it.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúBefore the war I never thought of getting married‚Äî maybe after 30 or something. But when the war started my mind changed. Every night I am awakened by airstrikes. I live near the sea, and the helicopters are coming from the sea. Whenever I hear them, I am thinking: ‚ÄòWhat if this one is for me?‚Äù And if these shots are for me‚Äîhow is it going to feel?‚Äô A few months ago my uncles family‚Äîthey died, to the very last, including the baby. They were sheltering in a school that got bombed. They say when something like that happens, you don‚Äôt feel anything. So if it happens to me, this is what I hope. But sometimes you get trapped beneath the rubble. And it takes a long time to die. It‚Äôs very scary to think about. For the first time in my life I‚Äôve started to feel like I need someone‚Äî someone to tell me that everything‚Äôs going to be okay. Four months ago I became engaged. Her name is Lama. She‚Äôs the sister of my best friend Kareem, who was killed in a bombing last year. I was driving to her house today. I‚Äôd put on jeans, and was smelling very good, and I started thinking: ‚ÄòMaybe I shouldn‚Äôt be so happy. Because things are so bad for everyone.‚Äô But if I‚Äôm being honest, we are very happy. It is maybe even better than being in love in a normal situation. Sometimes when I wake up from the airstrikes: I‚Äôll send her a very sweet message: ‚ÄòI hope you are very good,‚Äô and so on. This is something that is nothing during normal times. But it‚Äôs a bit different when you are checking if someone is alive. All these things, which used to seem like nothing, are everything to us now. I visit her two or three times a week. Every time I go to her house, we have like five minutes or so.  If she‚Äôs upset about Kareem, upset about the situation, afraid of the missiles, I‚Äôll calm her down. I‚Äôll give her a hug. It‚Äôs a very great feeling, honestly. I don‚Äôt know how to describe it. It‚Äôs not going to stop bullets, or bombs, but it makes you feel safe. By that I mean, at least I‚Äôm with her and she‚Äôs with me. If something happens to me, it is going to happen to her. So we going to be in the same situation. We will live together, or we will die together. And just knowing this, it makes me feel safe.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúMy whole life people have said to me: ‚ÄòYou are too kind, too sensitive.‚Äô When I interviewed for a schoolteacher position, the principal told me: ‚ÄòYou will never be able to control the students.‚Äô Because of this I built in my mind that I‚Äôm not a very strong person, you know? I decided to focus on my house, my family, my children. When the war started I was working as a data encoder; I spent all day on the laptop. But Doctors Without Borders said to me: ‚ÄòKholoud, there is no one left to ask. We need you to help organize our operations in the North.‚Äô And I‚Äôve done it. I organized a network of people on the ground. Everyone in the organization knows me now, respects me. And I‚Äôve done all of this while raising four children, and another four children who lost their parents. In December we spent fifteen days on the street because there were too many bombs. Nobody could sleep safely inside. I ate nothing during this time, zero. I just drank some water every two days. We were sheltering in a small corridor inside a school yard. My husband left us to look for food, and that‚Äôs when the bomb fell. When it falls close to you, you don‚Äôt hear anything. You just see the body parts flying through the air: the hand of someone, the leg of someone, the head of someone. My son comes to me and his face is blood. My daughter comes to me and she is clutching her chest. My other two children are holding their legs; I can‚Äôt tell how they are injured. There was no hospital left in Gaza City, so I brought them back to our house. Our neighbor is a doctor, so I asked him to come over. We discovered that one of my children had shrapnel in the head. The other three in the leg. There was no anesthesia, no stitches. We put something in the children‚Äôs mouth, and I held them down while he removed the shrapnel with the kitchen knife. You cannot imagine how the children were screaming. But we removed the shrapnel. And when we finished, I took the knife, and removed the shrapnel from my own leg. ‚ÄòToo kind, too sensitive.‚Äô I heard this my entire life. But I can tell you: another person lives inside you. And if the world forces you, you will find her.‚Äù üì∏ @nouralsaqa

caption: ‚ÄúI cannot cry. Before the war‚Äî any little thing, it would make me cry. But now I cannot make myself. I want to but I can‚Äôt, even when my heart is breaking. I used to be a schoolteacher; I love children. But now I see them walking in the streets with no shoes. They come into our clinic and you can see how tired they are. Some of them are mutilated: they‚Äôve lost a leg, or an arm. You see children crying because they cannot walk again. Yes, there is a lot of children like this now. But even the ones who aren‚Äôt injured are changing. Before the war it was not normal to find a child who wasn‚Äôt in school. There were organizations that would find the parents and force them to enroll. But now Gaza‚Äôs children haven‚Äôt been to school in two years. They‚Äôre changing. They‚Äôre beginning to think: ‚ÄòI will never go to school. I will just work to bring my family food or water.‚Äô Even my own daughter; she‚Äôs twelve years old. She was a leader in school and she dreamed to be a doctor. She has a cousin in Canada, the same age. They have video calls, and my daughter can see the difference. She sees how far behind she‚Äôs fallen, and recently she told me: ‚ÄòI won‚Äôt be a doctor anymore.‚Äô This broke my heart, but still, I could not cry. It‚Äôs like something is blocked in me. I don‚Äôt share my pain with anyone. I don‚Äôt share with my husband. I don‚Äôt share with my mother, or my father, or my sister. Because all these people come to me to feel safe. A few months ago when they bombed the house of my husband‚Äôs family‚ÄîI went to collect the body parts. It was too difficult for my husband. He lost fifteen members of his family that day. His mother, his father, his brother, were beneath the rubble. So I went. I had to start looking: this is the head for who? This arm, this leg, is for who? Afterwards I sat alone, and I tried to cry. I felt that if only I could cry, I will feel better. I will feel less full. But even then, I could not. I have a colleague in the work, who tells me: ‚ÄòKholoud, after the war, you are going to collapse. Because you do not cry.‚Äô‚Äù üì∏ @nouralsaqa

caption: ‚ÄúWe had one chance to leave Gaza, early in the war. At that time our lives had grown very difficult. We‚Äôd been displaced. We sat down and had a family discussion, and the consensus in the family was not to leave. We‚Äôd just learned that our house was still standing, so we thought: ‚ÄòWe‚Äôre luckier than others.‚Äô One month later the Philadelphi corridor was closed, and the option to leave was exhausted. But we still thought we would be OK. We thought the war would end soon, as we think now, as we thought a year ago, as we thought two years ago. And at least we were together. Our family has always been extremely close. I care for my patients, I care for my friends, but not the way I care for my family. Especially my mother. All people say that their mother is a saint, but she was actually a saint. She hated no one. She loved everyone. When I was a child she worked as a schoolteacher, and her school was next to mine, so in the mornings we would walk to school together. I don‚Äôt know why I remember this‚Äîbut she‚Äôd always walk between me and the sun. So that I could stand in her shadow. It‚Äôs a simple memory, but it means a lot to me. I was always the most attached to her. Maybe everyone in our family feels the same way, but this is my feeling. I told jokes only for her, so that she would laugh. I specialized in medicine just to make her happy. I was a resilient teenager. I wanted to be a writer. But she confronted me. She told me: ‚ÄòLife on Earth is a short journey, and you should help people. Because we believe in God. And we believe there is more than just this life.‚Äô Everything, all the things I have done, I have done to please her. And I let her down. I let her down. Because it was my decision. Three days before she was killed, I evacuated her to a safer place. And the safer place got bombed.‚Äù (1/2)
firstComment: I am so sorry for the loss of Dr. Kullab. I am sure his mother had been so proud of him and the work he is doing. Thanks to HONY and Dr. Kullab for sharing this story and illuminating the realities of the people in Gaza.  I hope Dr. Kullab does not keep blaming himself for the death of his mother, as he is not the one bombing civilians but trying to save their lives

caption: ‚ÄúAt one point, I hated Gaza. I just wanted out. I wanted to study in America and be this big director. I wanted to win an Oscar. All my dreams were overseas. I think I was just mad at how besieged Gaza was‚Äîit limits you in so many ways. Some of the men here are so narrow minded. I wanted to throw them all out of Gaza so that they could see the world, and then bring them back, with different views, and different thoughts. But there‚Äôs also a brilliance to the people here. Because it would take decades of research to learn what our trauma forces upon us at a very young age. You don‚Äôt have the privilege of disassociating from reality. You cannot ignore this shit. The drones, the rubble, the blood, the children fighting for food and water. It‚Äôs all around you. A white person living in Europe is able to say they don‚Äôt care about politics, because they‚Äôre not exposed to the firsthand effects. But if even one of the things that happen on a daily basis in Gaza, was to happen in the West, it would move nations. In political science class we used to learn about things like ethics, and human rights, and international law. But life in Gaza will teach you that these things are just propaganda. Propaganda that fooled us into believing that if only people knew what was going on, they‚Äôd stop it. It was this naive notion that led us, at least me and all of my friends, to film and document and speak and share on our stupid Instagrams. But I‚Äôve lost the will. It‚Äôs too exhausting. Everyone has disassociated from our reality. We have nothing to eat, but we have these phones. We get to watch our international friends going about their days normally. Who are we even talking to? You cannot rely on the conscience and moral compass of those in power. We‚Äôve tried for so long. It doesn‚Äôt work. You have to put pressure on them. You have to disrupt their systems. You have to move and mobilize and obstruct and protest and cost them things. It‚Äôs the only thing they listen to. Life in Gaza does teach you. For the longest time I wanted to leave, but now I don‚Äôt feel like I could bear living anywhere else in this world. Gaza feels like the only real place left on earth.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúWhen I entered Gaza the Israeli military had a rule: I was only allowed to bring in seven pounds of food. As I was weighing out protein bars, trying to get under the limit, I said to my husband: ‚ÄòHow sinister is this?‚Äô I‚Äôm a humanitarian aid worker. Why would there even be a limit on food? I‚Äôve worked in many places with extreme hunger, but what‚Äôs so jarring in this context is how cruel it is, how deliberate. I was in Gaza for two months; there‚Äôs no way to describe the horror of what‚Äôs happening. And I say this as a pediatric ICU doctor who sees children die as part of my work. Among our own staff we have doctors and nurses who are trying to treat patients while hungry, exhausted. They‚Äôre living in tents. Some of them have lost fifteen, twenty members of their families. In the hospital there are kids maimed by airstrikes: missing arms, missing legs, third degree burns. Often there‚Äôs not enough pain medication. But the children are not screaming about the pain, they‚Äôre screaming: ‚ÄòI‚Äôm hungry! I‚Äôm hungry!‚Äù I hate to only focus on the kids, because nobody should be starving. But the kids, it just haunts you in a different way. When my two months were finished, I didn‚Äôt want to leave. It‚Äôs a feeling I haven‚Äôt experienced in nearly twenty years of humanitarian assignments. But I felt ashamed. Ashamed to leave my Palestinian colleagues, who were some of the most beautiful and compassionate people that I‚Äôve ever met. I was ashamed as an American, as a human being, that we‚Äôve been unable to stop something that is so clearly a genocide. I remember when our bus pulled out of the buffer zone. Out the window on one side I could see Rafah, which was nothing but rubble. On the other side was lush, green Israel. When we exited the gate, the first thing I saw was a group of Israeli soldiers, sitting at a table, eating lunch. I‚Äôve never felt so nauseous seeing a table full of food.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúHer name is Rita. It comes from a poem by a well-known poet of Palestine. It‚Äôs a song that I used to sing, and my wife loves it too. So Rita is a product of love between me and my wife. I haven‚Äôt seen either of them in a year and a half. When the border opened last year, I sent them both out of the country. I hold a Master‚Äôs degree in Burns, Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery‚Äîand these skills are deeply needed in Gaza. So I chose to stay behind. Now the border is closed, and I couldn‚Äôt leave if I wanted to. I do my best to talk to Rita on WhatsApp every day. I‚Äôll ask about kindergarten, and her swimming lessons. I‚Äôll look at her latest drawings, and try to encourage her. But that‚Äôs it; I‚Äôm a WhatsApp father only. A few days ago she was ignoring me a bit, so I asked: ‚ÄòWhy don‚Äôt you talk to me?‚Äô She told me: ‚ÄòI feel like I forgot you a little bit.‚Äô My wife jumped in, and said: ‚ÄòNo, no, she‚Äôs kidding.‚Äô But I said: ‚ÄòShe doesn‚Äôt need to be kidding. She‚Äôs saying the truth.‚Äô I‚Äôve been gone most of her life. First with my studies in England, and now with this separation. I do feel guilty, yes. But if I had left, I‚Äôd feel even more guilty. There‚Äôd be a crack in my heart. It would come to me in my nightmares, every time I saw the suffering of my people. The first stage of this genocide was to destroy the health infrastructure, so there‚Äôd be no refuge for the dying. I happen to be part of an organization, Doctors Without Borders, with big abilities and big principles. I knew that if we worked together, and made the right decisions, and did the right things‚Äîwe‚Äôd be able to provide comfort to countless people. And that‚Äôs what we‚Äôve done. I‚Äôve co-managed a team that built a field hospital with 120 beds, and three surgical theaters running 24 hours. This is something I‚Äôll be proud of for years and years. And I hope one day Rita will understand. I‚Äôll ask her to read books and watch documentaries about the genocide. I‚Äôll ask her to understand that I couldn‚Äôt close my eyes to the suffering of our people. We must resist. And how do we resist? By existing. And how do we exist? By having a value. And in our family, our value is to serve others, more than we serve ourselves.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúOur first daughter‚Äôs name is Ashley. It‚Äôs a weird name in a Russian community. But she was the first American baby in our family, and we wanted an American name. We decided that if we ever had another daughter, her name would be Abigail. I‚Äôve always loved that name. But we weren‚Äôt in a rush to get pregnant again. I was young. And we never predicted that we‚Äôd have all these struggles. It wasn‚Äôt until the miscarriage that we decided to try fertility treatments. By then Ashley was already twelve. It was one of the most difficult periods of my life: the cycles, the shots. You keep going through the motions, hoping something good will happen. It steals all the joy from your current life. Eventually the doctors told us there was a zero percent chance without IVF, so we decided to give up and focus on our little family of three. Ashley promised me if she ever had a daughter, she‚Äôd name her Abigail. There was a bit of a grieving process; I‚Äôd spent so long envisioning the baby. But we focused on making Ashley‚Äôs childhood as special as possible. I tried to create little traditions. We always watched Fiddler on the Roof the night before Yom Kippur. And on the first day of school, I‚Äôd always cook chicken soup. Even after Ashley went to college, I would send her off to school with chicken soup. During her senior year I began to not feel well. At first I thought COVID, because it was during the pandemic. Then I thought early menopause, because I was forty-one already. But one sleepless night I found a box of pregnancy tests that had expired ten years earlier. They still worked. I used all ten of them, and each time there was the bright pink line. There was no joy at first. I was so afraid of having another miscarriage. It was a very difficult pregnancy, so I made a deal with God. I don‚Äôt know why, but I promised him that if I could carry to term, I wouldn‚Äôt color my hair until the birth. By the time she came my hair was very, very gray. How do I even describe it? So much joy. It‚Äôs a second season, a second wind. A few years ago we were preparing for early retirement. But now we‚Äôre busier than ever: planning a wedding for Ashley, and looking at preschools for Abigail."

caption: ‚ÄúWe were young when we had her. I was twenty-three, the mother was twenty; we weren‚Äôt planning to have kids yet. I don‚Äôt want to say the relationship fell apart because of our daughter. It was mostly us. We were going through a stressful time: I‚Äôd just lost my mother, she‚Äôd just lost her grandmother. We were going through an eviction and had to move into a shelter. We just handled our stress in different ways. She dealt with it by wanting to be young and dumb and free. We were arguing about everything, and I‚Äôm not good at arguing. I don‚Äôt like confrontation. I get agitated, antsy. Every time there was an argument, I‚Äôd get so angry that I‚Äôd have to leave the facility to get some air. I‚Äôve been that way since childhood. My mom and my dad were heavy addicts; they lost custody of me when I was four. I grew up in programs. I didn‚Äôt have nobody to show me affection. And it made me angry, I was an angry kid. I saw that other people had love, and understood it, and to be honest, I wasn‚Äôt okay with it. There are times where I still feel like that, sometimes even now as a father. But every time I look at her it goes away. It went away the moment she was born. When you held your first kid, did you see a glow around them? Did you ever see a glow? Because I saw a glow. And I felt it. It was like, holy shit.  I wanted to cry the first time I felt it, because I wasn‚Äôt sure what it was. I was confused. But as it gradually grew on me, I was like: OK, so this is what love is. And it felt beautiful. It made me want to be better. I don‚Äôt want my daughter seeing the side of me from when I was young and didn‚Äôt know how to cope with my anger. Right now I have her every day after school. There‚Äôs a counselor at her school: Mr. Gonzalez. I go to see him once, sometimes twice a week. He‚Äôs been very helpful. He‚Äôs teaching me how to cope with life, how to handle arguments with my baby‚Äôs mother. Now if she texts me twenty paragraphs about things that happened six years ago, I don‚Äôt fight back. I just don‚Äôt respond, until it‚Äôs time to get the baby.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúWhen I was fifteen I lost a younger brother to a guy who raped and killed him, and I took the law into my own hands. I don‚Äôt want to say much more to that effect, but when it happened, I lost faith in humanity. I didn‚Äôt trust anybody. Life became all about me, so I just survived. A lot of my family members still won‚Äôt talk to me because they remember a Johnny that wasn‚Äôt trustworthy. I became a wanderer, there‚Äôs no better way to say it. And one day ten years ago I wandered into this park looking for a place to sit down. I saw an old man playing chess, in exchange for donations. He was waiting for an oncomer so I came on. He beat me senseless. But it was my first taste of communication with a stranger sitting across from me. And I thought to myself: ‚ÄòI can do that too.‚Äô I bought myself a chess board. In the beginning I got the shit kicked out of me by strangers from all over the world. But I grew game after game, learning the fundamentals, then learning all the other stuff. And now I teach them to anybody who wants to play. I get donations, but it‚Äôs not the money that‚Äôs the fruit of my take. It‚Äôs when people sit down. I call it fruit, is that weird? Because when you share an activity with someone for fifteen minutes, a half hour‚Äîit nourishes your soul. Me looking at you, us laughing, doing bad moves, good moves‚Äî it‚Äôs all so nourishing. Because of chess I got to witness the difference between good and evil. So many have sat across from me that are so good‚Äî honest people with great, great hearts. I knew that very first day that this seat would make my life more significant. I knew as long as I kept sitting here, people would keep coming. And there is so much fruit that you get from people. Not all the people, can‚Äôt go that far. There are some around here that I would like to strangle, I‚Äôm not shitting. But we maintain. Because look, I‚Äôve got problems too. And I‚Äôm not looking to blow the house down.‚Äù

In the hallway outside the operating room, I told my dad and sisters: ‚ÄòGuys, let‚Äôs wipe away our tears. We have to be strong for Mom.‚Äô‚Äô But when we walked into the room, before we could even say a word, Mom pointed at the wrap on her head and said: ‚ÄòChiquita Banana Lady.‚Äô And everyone started laughing, and snot crying. I mean, who does that? Who wakes up from brain surgery and thinks: ‚ÄòI need a joke that will make my family laugh?‚Äô But that‚Äôs who she was. Other people first, always. It was a horrible form of brain cancer. Those last fifteen months we watched it take everything from her. She was paralyzed on one side of her body. She couldn‚Äôt walk. The tumor was pressing against the speech center of her brain, so she slowly lost her ability to speak. Words started disappearing. It was very frustrating for her. She‚Äôd know what she wanted to say, and she‚Äôd reach, and reach, and reach‚Äî but it wasn‚Äôt there. I couldn‚Äôt bear to see her get frustrated. At the time I was a freshman in college. She‚Äôd ask me about school, and I‚Äôd rush to finish her sentences as soon as she opened her mouth. I‚Äôd be like: ‚ÄòMom, do you mean this?‚Äô Our biggest fear was that we‚Äôd lose her before she passed away‚Äî you know what I mean? But it never happened. The disease ‚Äòtook everything,‚Äô but it never touched her soul. Toward the end she was down to just a few words, but two of those words were: ‚Äòunconditional love.‚Äù They were unlikely words to hold onto. They weren‚Äôt easy to say, so many syllables. But ‚Äòunconditional love‚Äô became her answer to everything. It was her replacement for all the sentences and paragraphs she could not say. I remember our last conversation. I think she was trying to tell me to take care of my sister, but she couldn‚Äôt quite get the words out. She got so frustrated that she started to cry. I couldn‚Äôt bear to see it, so I just started talking. I told her: ‚ÄòMom, I‚Äôm going to dedicate my life to finding treatments for people like you.‚Äô She looked so tired, but she gave me the biggest smile ever. Well, the biggest half-smile ever. And she said: ‚ÄòUnconditional Love.‚Äô‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúI had an abusive relationship, and I don‚Äôt want to talk too much about that. But for me coming to U.S. was an escape. Two years ago I came, with only $700. I was a little afraid but I had a lot of hopes. This is a land of hope for me. In Russia I studied to be software engineer, but I don‚Äôt know what is wrong with me. Here I could not get software engineer job. For a long time I worked as a medical receptionist, but I was fired in May. I lost my place. I am living now in shelter, which is the ideal situation for me. I don‚Äôt have to pay crazy money for New York apartment;  I can use all my money for study. Right now I am studying to be a truck driver. Maybe this job seems ‚Äònot too high,‚Äô but I love it. I am introvert, so I don‚Äôt mind being alone. I will become a driver and will see all of U.S. I want to see Oregon. I want to see North Carolina. I‚Äôm so much interested in national parks. Right now I am cleaning apartments: one day, $100. And that $100 buys me one hour of road lessons. I‚Äôm almost finished; on July 20th I have my road exam. I‚Äôm so grateful that this city, this state, gave me such support. I‚Äôm grateful to this country where I have everything to realize my dreams. When I get this job, I will pay the taxes and everything. Even living in shelter, this is a good time for me. This morning I had road lesson, so this afternoon I bring my book to the beach. It‚Äôs absolutely amazing. There is sun, it is good weather. I can come here, breathe the sea, see children playing. They say it is better to not tell your dreams, but I would love one day to find a happy relationship and have kids. But even if I don‚Äôt meet someone, I plan to born a baby. I will use a bank of sperm. I want to try to be a mother, because I have a lot of love inside and a lot to teach and a lot to share. I‚Äôve learned that I‚Äôm very strong. I‚Äôve had a lot of hard situations: a lot, a lot of hard situations. But I have a fire inside. I can feel it. It keeps me going forward. I know what I want, and I know that I have the power inside me to make it come true.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúI treat every trash can like it‚Äôs my personal refrigerator. The food pantries are alright: groceries, canned goods. The only problem is you need a place to store all that stuff. If you ever end up homeless on the street, and need something immediately, lose your pride and go straight for the trash can. Get in there; just don‚Äôt eat nothing that‚Äôs spoiled. I found some Fluffy‚Äôs Chicken in here just a few minutes ago.  Earlier today I found a turkey and swiss wrap, still rolled and everything. God Bless America. If you know where to look you will never go hungry in this country. Don‚Äôt even get me started on the supermarkets. Western Beef dumps all their expired food in the back by the receiving area. And if you want dessert, just go to Dunkin Donuts at closing time. Nothing in that garbage that‚Äôs actually garbage. Big bags of all your favorites: the jellies, the chocolate tops, the strawberry tops. I‚Äôve gotten whole cheesecakes from The Cheesecake Factory, one day past their expiration date. Maybe you don‚Äôt need any food. Maybe it‚Äôs money you want. Again, look no further than the trash can. Let me introduce you to the nickel bottle deposit: any aluminum, plastic, or glass is refundable. I know a place I can go right now and get $80 in bottles. You know how many people rely on that to live every day? That‚Äôs why I love this country. Where else in the world can you go in a garbage can and come out with money?  I‚Äôve had Facebook girlfriends from other countries, they tell me: ‚ÄòWe can‚Äôt do that here.‚Äô I‚Äôm like: ‚ÄòYou‚Äôre telling me, you can‚Äôt go into any trash can and find everything you need for your household?‚Äô People really do starve in other countries. And that‚Äôs why I say it: God Bless America.‚Äù

caption: I‚Äôm looking for NYC photographers who document their own communities to participate in an exhibition being hosted in one of New York City‚Äôs most iconic locations. Any documentary photography of people will be considered, but special consideration will be given to street portraiture. I‚Äôm looking to feature a diverse group of photographers and communities, so please spread the word to anyone you know who matches this description. Ten photographers will be chosen. Each photographer will receive $10,000 and will also have their work spotlighted on Humans of New York. Photographers: please email a few examples of your work to dearnysubmissions@gmail.com. Please include your website, social media handles, the neighborhood where you live, and a little bit about yourself. What‚Äôs your story?

caption: ‚ÄúThe lowest moments usually come from people who love you but don‚Äôt understand you. They see you struggling, and say: ‚ÄòWhy don‚Äôt you just stop doing it?‚Äô But if they knew how important it was to me, they would never ask that. I had a little success in my late twenties. I was part of a band that signed to a record label, but we never had any hit music. It was mainly local stuff. Most of my thirties was working two jobs, struggling to pay bills, playing a late-night slot on a Tuesday night in a room with no people there, or maybe just a couple of my friends. It‚Äôs not that I felt disrespected, just not noticed. I guess obscure would be a good word. You‚Äôre lugging your guitar around everywhere. Nothing‚Äôs happening. It feels like you‚Äôre trying to hammer a nail with a banana. Those are the years where you say: ‚ÄòMan, is this really what I want to be doing? Can I live like this and be happy?‚Äô But every time I tried to put my guitar down, I‚Äôd find myself writing a poem, or writing a lyric, or trying to write a riff. Turns out that I did need to be creative to be happy, more than I needed to be successful. It‚Äôs been a long journey. It‚Äôs like any other small business; you‚Äôve got to build it one brick at a time. Even though my thirties were some tough years, it was during those years that my songwriting began to improve incredibly. Really talented musicians began to notice, and they were like: ‚ÄòMan, I love your stuff. I want to be in your band.‚Äô That‚Äôs when it all started to come together. My current band is called @tentonmojo. We‚Äôre playing a show tonight, and there will probably be like 80 or 100 people there. I‚Äôm forty-three, and I‚Äôm finally putting out stuff that other people are relating to. You know how music has this way of sinking into your memory, and becoming connected to a certain time in your life? I‚Äôm hoping that might happen tonight for some of those eighty people. With my music, finally.‚Äù
firstComment: ‚ÄèHello guys, I am Mohsen from North Gaza. We are working on distributing food to displaced families and the starving in the North. We have a donation campaign. caption: When I tried to interview Marwa, the internet in Gaza was so bad I couldn‚Äôt hear half of her words. She then sent me a written follow-up, which was so moving, and so beautifully written, that I‚Äôve ditched the interview altogether and am including it here in full: ‚ÄúIsrael bombed our house into a pile of rubble and dust. Everyone in it‚Äî my mother, my father, my four sisters, my brother, my baby niece‚Äî became a memory in the same instant. During the war, the home had become our lifeline. Comfort wasn‚Äôt always in words. It was in a shared cup of tea in the dark. It was my mother holding our hands, her presence a silent promise that we were not alone. It was my sisters distracting the children with stories. We would huddle together, our physical closeness a shield against the terrifying sounds outside. It‚Äôs probably a mercy that the house is now gone, because I don‚Äôt think my heart could bear to see the physical emptiness of the rooms where so much life once existed. It‚Äôs the ‚Äòunimportant‚Äô moments, the background noise of a living family, that I miss the most. I miss the sound of my father‚Äôs key in the door at the end of the day. I miss my mother‚Äôs hand on my forehead, checking for a fever that wasn‚Äôt there, just out of habit. I miss arguing with Nour about politics and then laughing about it two minutes later. I miss Mona‚Äôs quiet smile from across the room, a look that says: ‚ÄòI understand. I miss Ayat bursting into my room to show me a funny video. I miss the boys debating which one of them was the better gamer. Where all that beautiful noise used to be‚Äîthere is nothing but profound silence. If I had one more moment with each of them, I would simply say: ‚ÄòThank you.‚Äô To my father: ‚ÄòThank you for believing in me more than I ever believed in myself.‚Äô To my mother: ‚ÄòThank you for every silent sacrifice I was too young or too busy to notice.‚Äô To my sisters and brothers: ‚ÄòThank you for being the irreplaceable pieces of my childhood and my heart.‚Äô And if I could sit all of them together one more time, the whole family, I would say to them: ‚ÄòI see you. I see everything you did for me, for us. And I am so incredibly grateful.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúThe shift started like any other. I was making my rounds when around 2 pm I heard a bombing; it sounded very close. My family lives relatively near the hospital. Usually, when a bombing is that close, I would call them immediately. But on that day I didn‚Äôt call. I don‚Äôt know why. Maybe I‚Äôd grown desensitized. But after an hour I began to notice that the nurses were acting shifty around me. I was summoned to a case in the emergency room, and as we were walking down the hallway, one of the nurses asked if I‚Äôd heard from my family. That‚Äôs when I knew. I started running to the ER. The first person I found was my father. He‚Äôd been in the explosion area; he was stunned. My sister was next to him, she was also in shock. I asked about my mother and the nurse told me that she was in the ICU. It wasn‚Äôt true. But that‚Äôs what he told me, so he could get me alone. The ICU is three floors up from the ER, so I immediately began running up the stairs. The nurse ran after me. We passed the first floor, the second floor, and then he stopped me forcefully. He told me: ‚ÄòI‚Äôm sorry. I didn‚Äôt know how to tell you. But your mother is deceased.‚Äô I fell to the floor. And I can‚Äôt remember everything here, I was in shock. But they brought me to the forensics room and led me to a giant, white bag. I unzipped it. And I saw her face. She looked as good as alive. She had bled out through her legs, so her face was untouched. And I wanted so bad to kiss her in that moment. So I kissed her. And I began to hug her. But they pulled me away and they covered her again. I‚Äôm sorry. I‚Äôm sorry for the tears. But this is the first time I‚Äôve talked to anyone about this. I have to be strong for my family. Especially because my father is a paraplegic now; it‚Äôs a lot of responsibility. I need to be the emotional sponge for everyone else. caption: ‚ÄúAll day I am thinking: your son, your son. You need to do something for your son. Yazan is not a normal boy, he‚Äôs very disabled. But he‚Äôs the most precious thing I‚Äôve got. Before the war he was improving so much. He was going to therapy. He was making good eye contact. He‚Äôs very shy, he cannot express his feelings. But I would take him to visit the neighbors and everyone loved him. He‚Äôs a lovely boy: he holds my head, he kisses my cheeks. Right before the war we had a surgery on his legs. At that time he was five years old. When the doctors removed his casts I brought him home from the hospital, and I told my daughters and my wife to close their eyes. When they opened their eyes again, Yazan was walking. We‚Äôll never forget this moment; we had so much hope that he‚Äôd be a normal boy. But all the clinics have been closed now for two years. He‚Äôs had no therapy. Nothing has been done for him, nothing. Now if he walks three steps he falls down. Before the war he‚Äôd started to make sentences with a few words: ‚ÄòI need bread, I need water.‚Äô Now if he wants something, he‚Äôll just catch me by the arm and show me. And he‚Äôs doing this thing now, where he jerks his arms and legs. This is something we‚Äôve never seen before. We thought we would always go forward. We thought that he would be a normal boy. But now I am watching him deteriorate before my eyes. I have a good job; I work on a medical team. But still, I have no power. It takes all my power just to keep him from dying. Last year he got very bad diarrhea. There was no drinkable water. All of the pharmacies were empty. But I heard of a pharmacy six kilometers away with diarrhea medicine. I was so tired. No car, no fuel, no donkey cart. It was like horrible American action movie: there was bombing, shooting from tanks, shooting from helicopter. But I walked six kilometers, and I got him some medicine. And we managed to stop the diarrhea. Anything he needs, I will do. I have two hands. In one of these hands I carry all the problems of my work, all the problems of the war, raising my four daughters with no food, no water, no shelter, no electricity. And in the other hand, I carry Yazan.‚Äù üì∏ by @nouralsaqa

caption: ‚ÄúI went to Harvard for my Master‚Äôs, but still, I‚Äôm always thinking: ‚ÄòThis can end at any moment. At any moment the leadership is going to decide I wasn‚Äôt the right black guy.‚Äô It‚Äôs always fight-or-flight. It always feels like the platform I‚Äôm standing on is crumbling. It‚Äôs just a fact: it‚Äôs easier for me to lose everything than someone who doesn‚Äôt look like me. When those people slip, there will be people who look like them, who have done what they‚Äôre trying to do, who can step in to help them. But there aren‚Äôt any doctors in my family; my parents were janitors. They didn‚Äôt speak English. We lived in section eight housing. When I was taking all these tests, nobody knew what was going on. I had no understanding of how hard it would be to become a surgeon. And I guess that ignorance helped me in a way; it allowed me to start the journey. But imagery is also so important. When you never see a person that looks like you doing something, it‚Äôs hard to believe that you deserve to do it. There weren‚Äôt many black people in my medical school. So when I got into Columbia‚Äôs surgery program, I was like: ‚ÄòLemme see what white people I‚Äôm going to be with.‚Äô I turned on the video where they introduce our co-residents, and the first person I saw was a black Dominican woman. caption: ‚ÄúI‚Äôve closed my social media. From Gaza it‚Äôs all bad news: someone‚Äôs dying, someone‚Äôs been bombed, someone‚Äôs been displaced from their home. Then everywhere else in the world, you see things working so smoothly. Everyone is living their lives. Literally the smallest thing that they do: it makes me jealous. The smallest thing, like eating ice cream. This is my favorite food. And I‚Äôve gone two years without any ice cream. I don‚Äôt want to feel envious of anyone, so I‚Äôm trying not to see it. I‚Äôm still trying to treat myself in whatever small ways I can: like doing my hair, or maybe having henna dye on my hands. After work I will try to sit with my sisters, so we can connect, and say about our dreams. One of my dreams is for us all to live on an empty farm, a quiet place outside all the world. Two of our cousins have already passed away in a bombing. Four of my nieces and nephews were injured. I can‚Äôt lose anyone else. I can‚Äôt, I won‚Äôt be able to take it. My family is everything to me. Right now our home is partially destroyed, but we are still living in it. Because we don‚Äôt have anywhere else to go. Every day when I come home from work, my two-year old niece is waiting for me at the front door. Her name is Hanan; it means kindness. And when she hugs me it‚Äôs like a battery has charged in my heart. Literally all of her life has been in this war. Whenever she hears the sound of a plane, she covers her ears and says: ‚ÄòBoom! Boom! Boom!‚Äô She never goes anywhere. She never meets new people. We are her entire world. We do everything we can to protect her, to give her a childhood. Her birthday was two weeks ago. We had dancing all night. There was bombing all around us, but we just turned up the volume and tried to disconnect from all the noise. Sugar is impossible to get in Gaza now; but we gathered all the sugar we could. Everyone contributed. And with this sugar we made a cake, and cinnamon rolls, and sweet tea with mint. Hanan eats nothing but canned food; no snacks, no treats. So when she saw that cake, she started to scream. All the children started to scream; you can‚Äôt imagine their joy. It was maybe my best moment ever, in all of the war.‚Äù

caption: ‚ÄúI cannot forget a minute of that day. When I tell you this, it is like I‚Äôm seeing it in front of my face on a movie screen. At 3 AM drones appeared outside the windows of the hospital. Most of my colleagues had already fled. I forgive all of them; few beliefs can override the desire to save one‚Äôs own soul. But I could not leave. There were hundreds of patients, and few medical staff remaining. If the last of us left, these patients would have died. The hospital staff assembled in the lobby where we were stripped, handcuffed, blindfolded, and marched into the freezing night. Beneath my blindfold I could see hundreds of fighters with machine guns. I could hear the screams of my colleagues being beaten. My fear was so high I was close to cardiac arrest. Someone speaking weak Arabic put a gun to my head and told me I‚Äôd never see my children again. He asked: ‚ÄòWhere is Hamas? Where are the Hostages?‚Äô I told him: ‚ÄòI‚Äôm just a nurse; I disagree entirely with October 7th.‚Äô But these guys did not care. They beat us all. The lorries came to transport us to the detention center. At the door of the lorry stood the strongest of their fighters, body-builders. And before entering each detainee received the three hardest punches we will ever receive in our lives. When we arrived we were made to lie on the ground, and they put dogs on us. The dogs had muzzles, but we could not see through our blindfolds. All around me was barking and screaming; I thought my colleagues were being eaten. I was detained for several weeks. The conditions were so bad I prayed to die. One of the prison guards, exactly one, I can accept as my neighbor. The rest had hatred in their eyes. Some spoke English; so I tried to reason with them. I pointed out that half of the detainees had debilitating medical conditions. Some were eighty years old. One man was mentally incapacitated. I asked the guards: ‚ÄòHow could these people possibly be Hamas?‚Äô But for every claim‚Äîthey‚Äôd have a response. Some reason all of us were guilty. Even when I said: ‚ÄòI‚Äôm a nurse,‚Äô they replied: ‚ÄòOh, so you treated terrorists.‚Äô To them, every Palestinian deserves to suffer. And nothing you say‚Äînothing‚Äî will convince them otherwise.‚Äù
